    <p class="text-gray-300">points  <span class="math">(\\pm \\sqrt{s}, \\pm \\sqrt{s})</span>  (signs chosen independently) of order 4 defined over  <span class="math">\\mathbf{F}_p</span> . The group structure of the 4-torsion on  <span class="math">\\mathcal{E}_{d_0}</span>  that is defined over  <span class="math">\\mathbf{F}_p</span>  is thus  <span class="math">\\mathbf{Z}_2 \\times \\mathbf{Z}_4</span>  and has order 8. Therefore 8 must divide  <span class="math">\\#\\mathcal{E}_{d_0}(\\mathbf{F}_p)</span> , which contradicts our assumption that the group order is 4r for r prime. Hence,  <span class="math">d_0</span>  is a square.</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">We know that the twist  <span class="math">\\mathcal{E}&#x27;_{d_0}</span>  is birationally equivalent to  <span class="math">\\mathcal{E}_{1/d_0}</span> , and we have already shown that  <span class="math">d_0</span>  is a square, so  <span class="math">1/d_0</span>  is a square. We can apply Lemma 1 with  <span class="math">d_0</span>  replaced by  <span class="math">1/d_0</span> , which means that  <span class="math">d = -(d_0 + 1)</span> , and obtain that  <span class="math">\\#\\mathcal{E}_{-(d_0+1)}(\\mathbf{F}_p) = \\#\\mathcal{E}_{1/d_0}(\\mathbf{F}_p) = 4r&#x27;</span> . Now looking at the 4-torsion defined over  <span class="math">\\mathbf{F}_p</span>  as above yields that  <span class="math">-(d_0+1)</span>  is a square in  <span class="math">\\mathbf{F}_p</span> .</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">The minimality of  <span class="math">d_0</span> . All our selected twisted Edwards curves satisfy the conditions of the previous two lemmas. Therefore, one can choose to work with the isogenous curves defined by  <span class="math">d_0</span>  or  <span class="math">-(d_0+1)</span> , whichever is more convenient. The isogenous curves and their twists have the same orders as the original curves and their twists. Therefore all conditions required in the curve selection are satisfied with the added benefit of a small d-value.</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">We argue that  <span class="math">d_0</span>  is of minimal absolute value defining a curve that satisfies the search criteria. Assume that A is a coefficient with minimal absolute value that yields a desired curve when minimizing for the Montgomery parameter (like the values for A in our examples). A search that minimizes the absolute value of the parameter d in the twisted Edwards model  <span class="math">\\mathcal{E}_d</span> , must find the value  <span class="math">d_0</span>  (or  <span class="math">-(d_0 + 1)</span> ) first since A = <span class="math">-(4d_0+2)</span> . Without loss of generality, let  <span class="math">|d_0| &lt; |d_0+1|</span> , i.e.  <span class="math">d_0 &gt; 0</span> , otherwise interchange  <span class="math">d_0</span>  and  <span class="math">-(d_0 + 1)</span> . Indeed, assume that a  <span class="math">d_1</span>  with  <span class="math">|d_1| &lt; |d_0|</span>  leads to a curve that satisfies all criteria. Let  <span class="math">A_1 = -(4d_1 + 2)</span> . By Lemma 3,  <span class="math">d_1</span>  and  <span class="math">-(d_1+1)</span>  are squares, then by Lemma 2,  <span class="math">\\#\\mathcal{E}_{d_1}(\\mathbf{F}_p) = \\#\\mathcal{E}_{\\hat{d}_1}(\\mathbf{F}_p) = \\#E_{A_1}(\\mathbf{F}_p)</span> , where  <span class="math">\\hat{d}_1 = -(A_1 - 2)/(A_1 + 2)</span>  and  <span class="math">\\#\\mathcal{E}&#x27;_{d_1}(\\mathbf{F}_p) = \\mathcal{E}_{-(d_1 + 1)}(\\mathbf{F}_p)</span>  <span class="math">= \\#\\mathcal{E}_{1/\\hat{d}_1}(\\mathbf{F}_p) = \\#E_{-A_1}(\\mathbf{F}_p)</span> . This means that the curve  <span class="math">E_{A_1}</span>  satisfies the search criteria.</p>

