      <h3 id="sec-3.4" class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8">3.4 Curve properties</h3>

    <p class="text-gray-300">In both families of curves, note that for primes of the form 2 <sup>&alpha;</sup> &minus;&gamma;, the bitlengths of r and r <sup>0</sup> differ by 1, since |t| &gamma; in general; for primes of the form 2 <sup>&alpha;</sup>(2<sup>&beta;</sup> &minus;&gamma;)&minus;1, the bitlengths of r and r <sup>0</sup> are always equal when &gamma; 6= 0. The curves in Table 2 can be used in different curve models: in the twisted Edwards model, in the Montgomery model for implementing Montgomery ladders, and also in the original Edwards model allowing complete addition formulas [11]. The latter can be seen as follows. Since p &equiv; 3 (mod 4), E<sup>A</sup> is birationally equivalent to an Edwards curve by [7, Theorem 3.4]. Using the maps discussed in [7, Section 3], one can show that E<sup>A</sup> : y <sup>2</sup> = x <sup>3</sup> + Ax<sup>2</sup> + x is birationally equivalent to E<sup>&minus;</sup>1/d : x <sup>2</sup> + y <sup>2</sup> = 1 &minus; (1/d)x 2y 2 . For all of our curves, d is a square in Fp, so &minus;1/d is not a square, which means that the addition law on E<sup>&minus;</sup>1/d is complete. All of the curves in Table 2 allow for an efficient map from a subset of their Fp-rational points to bit strings of a certain length, such that they are indistinguishable from uniform random bitstrings of the same length (see [10], which is based on [29]). However, note that curves defined over pseudo-Mersenne primes are more suitable for achieving indistinguishability than those over Montgomery-friendly primes because for the latter primes p, the value (p+ 1)/2 is further away from a power of 2 (see [10, &sect;2.6]). The prime-order Weierstrass curves presented in Table 1 are similar in their basic properties to the NIST curves, as they have the same curve model, share the parameter a = &minus;3, and include prime fields of the same bit lengths as the ones for the NIST curves [58]. However, we stress that the curves in Table 1 do not allow any ro